‚úÖ Approved the contribution.
Comment: The task is clear, but an optimal/shortest solution is not obvious. It is very feasible to solve using several case distinctions, although in order to code it quickly, one needs some additional thoughts.
The way the Goal is phrased, I would not expect factors like "(X+2)" but rather "(X--2)". Personally, I would prefer a note/an example using "(X+a)" for negative roots.

Input
* Please delete "There is no limit to the numbers of roots."

Output
* Please rewrite as:
All roots in one line in ascending order and separated by spaces.

Constraints
* Please add ‚ÄúAll roots are positive integers.‚Äù

Cases
* In all the cases, please replace ‚Äúk‚Äù with *different* integers.

* In all the cases, please fix the output and remove all the trailing spaces, e.g. ‚Äú1 2 ‚Äù should be fixed as ‚Äú1 2‚Äù.

* I don‚Äôt see how the ‚ÄúUltimate‚Äù cases are harder than the ‚ÄúHard‚Äù cases. Having more roots doesn‚Äôt make them harder. I would suggest to at least include some 4-digit roots in the ‚ÄúUltimate‚Äù cases to make it slightly better.

* (optional) Suggest to change the input so that
(a) there are negative roots, and/or
(b) there are non-integer roots, and/or
(c) the factors of the polynomial are not always sorted, and/or
(d) sometimes there are repeating factors, e.g. 14(X-2)(X-7)(X-7)(X-29), and in such cases, the output should not repeat the roots.

Stub generator
* Please add a write statement e.g. ‚Äúwrite roots‚Äù.

Thanks.

I think N should be formatted as a variable. You can also remove the line in constraints as there are none, unless you want to indicate there are no negative roots.
Also none of the tests have duplicates but the output example does.
I modified, i added a, c, d option
I add a negative root in the goal
It's better though I wonder if you mean no root is larger than 1000 or if there is a limit to the number of roots.
